Why This Document Exists
========================

Making a free-as-in-freedom replacement for the Inform Designer's
Manual is necessary for several philosophical and practical reasons:

1.  Adaptability and Evolution: The Inform compiler and standard 
    library continue to evolve, introducing new features and
    functionalities. The proprietary nature of the Inform Designer's
    Manual makes it challenging to update and adapt the documentation
    to reflect these changes. This inability to update the
    documentation can lead to confusion and frustration for users,
    especially newcomers, who may struggle to utilize the latest
    features without accurate and up-to-date documentation. A manual
    that freely allows changes allows the community to collaboratively
    update and maintain the documentation, ensuring its accuracy and
    relevance as Inform 6 evolves.
2.  Avoiding Fragmentation: As the Inform Designer's Manual becomes 
    outdated, the community has resorted to publishing change logs and 
    supplementary materials. While helpful, this approach can lead to 
    fragmentation and make it difficult for users to find the 
    necessary information. A single, up-to-date, and freely accessible 
    manual would provide a centralized and reliable source of 
    information for all users.
3.  Community Ownership and Contribution: Free-as-in-freedom 
    documentation allows for community ownership and contribution.
    Individuals can contribute their knowledge and expertise to
    improve documentation, providing more comprehensive and accurate
    resources. This collaborative approach fosters a sense of shared
    responsibility and ownership, benefiting the entire IF community.
4.  Accessibility and Collaboration: Information should be freely
    accessible to all. By creating a replacement for the Inform
    Designer's Manual that can be freely altered and shared, we remove
    barriers and foster a more inclusive and collaborative
    environment, encouraging more involvement in the interactive
    fiction community.
5.  Ethical Considerations: The principles of free software, as
    outlined in the GNU Philosophy <https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/>,
    emphasize the ethics of free software and the importance of
    sharing knowledge and empowering users. Free documentation
    <https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/free-doc.en.html> applies these
    principles to the software's documentation. With a
    free-as-in-freedom replacement for the Inform Designer's Manual,
    we align with these ethical considerations and contribute to a
    culture of collaboration within the IF community. This philosophy
    empowers users to learn, adapt, and improve the documentation,
    fostering a more inclusive and participatory environment for
    creating interactive fiction.

In summary, creating a free-as-in-freedom replacement for the Inform
Designer's Manual is essential for ensuring the adaptability,
accessibility, and collaborative development of Inform 6
documentation. It fosters community ownership, avoids fragmentation,
and aligns with the ethical principles of free software and
documentation. By undertaking this project, we can empower new
generations of interactive fiction creators and ensure the continued
growth and vibrancy of the IF community.

